  "prompt": "How many 3-digit numbers can be formed using only 1, 2, 3?",
  "response": "Let $S = \\{1, 2, 3\\}$. We want to form 3-digit numbers using only the digits in $S$.\nSince we can use each digit in $S$ multiple times, we can choose any of the three digits for each position in the 3-digit number.\nFor the first digit (hundreds place), we have 3 choices (1, 2, or 3).\nFor the second digit (tens place), we have 3 choices (1, 2, or 3).\nFor the third digit (ones place), we have 3 choices (1, 2, or 3).\nSince each digit can be chosen independently, the total number of 3-digit numbers that can be formed is the product of the number of choices for each digit.\nTherefore, the total number of 3-digit numbers is $3 \\times 3 \\times 3 = 3^3 = 27$.\n\nThe possible 3-digit numbers are:\n111, 112, 113,\n121, 122, 123,\n131, 132, 133,\n211, 212, 213,\n221, 222, 223,\n231, 232, 233,\n311, 312, 313,\n321, 322, 323,\n331, 332, 333\n\nThe number of 3-digit numbers that can be formed using only 1, 2, 3 is $3 \\times 3 \\times 3 = 27$.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{27}$",
